Also, as a general note. While functional tests (i.e. tempest) can test particular scenario, in unit tests we use to try to cover logic behind tested method.

So, in case of simple example:

    class MyClass(object):

        def __init__(self, arg):
            self.attr = arg

        def method1(self, bar=100):
            if bar:
                self.attr = bar
            else:
                raise Exception("blah")

            return True


    import unittest


    class TestMyClass(unittest.TestCase):

        def test_create_object(self):
            obj = MyClass(1)
            self.assertEqual(obj.attr, 1)

        def test_create_object_missing_attribute(self):
            self.assertRaises(TypeError, MyClass)

        def test_method1(self):
            obj = MyClass(1)
            self.assertTrue(obj.method1(10))
            self.assertEqual(obj.attr, 10)

        def test_method1_negative(self):
            obj = MyClass(1)
            self.assertTrue(obj.method1(-10))
            self.assertEqual(obj.attr, -10)

        def test_method1_zero(self):
            obj = MyClass(1)
            self.assertRaises(Exception, obj.method1, 0)

here, we try to run tests against method "method1" with several different inputs - so the three independent tests. Note, that amount of test methods for single thing (creating object, calling method1 method) is at least twice, and it's increasing on tested method complexity.

Also. We usually name the test as the corresponding tested function/method, so in this case it should be "test_move_annotation_to_crd" (or, depending on the taste "test__move_annotation_to_crd", since this is a private method).

