manifests/healthcheck.pp.message:
Some of the existing implementations don't follow this unfortunately, but generally speaking we should avoid automatic inclusion.

Adding include works well in the deployment which uses hieradata to define all parameters but doesn't work in the deployment which uses the explicit parameter values in class definition.
For example if we add "include glance::api" then the following example doesn't work because of resource re-declaration, and we are forced to put glance::healthcheck first.

```
class { 'glance::api':
  ...
}

class { 'glance::healthcheck':
  detailed => false
}
```

So to avoid such enforced ordering we should avoid including classes in this later and leave that composition to upper later like puppet-tripleo or own manifests to define whole resources.

